ectures at the regularly scheduled class time it will also be helpful for the students if they can get the lectures asynchronously (i.e., at other times in the day). Some of our students have returned home to other parts of the world and requiring them to watch a lecture at 3am in the morning is difficult. Also some students might experience localized technical difficulties, or we may even experience at times some widescale interruptions. These sorts of issues can be greatly alleviated if we are offering asynchronous content delivery.â€       Teach Online   Recommended for teaching online and office hours.      Blackboard Collaborate         Blackboard Collaborate Instructions   Get started   Sign In at https://uic.blackboard.com , using Sign In button, then enter your UIC netid and password.   Instructions and Videos    What is a Course Room    Video: How to use Blackboard Collaborate    Video: Blackboard Collaborate Tour for Faculty/Students    Video: How to see what students see (Student Preview)    Video: How to create tests/exams    How to record your Blackboard sessions    How to invite (non-UIC) attendees to your session    How to use Piazza with Blackboard         Blackboard Collaborate Notes, FAQs, Alternatives   Notes   Recommended for teaching, office hours, and is already fully integrated into Blackboard Course sites.  Also great for Office Hours for Faculty and TAs.  You or your TA will have to moderate discussions if students present or ask questions during a session.  Dial-in phone numbers are available for sessions when host or student has trouble with audio/mic or internet connection.  iPads : Application sharing is not currently supported on mobile devices (including iPads) or for screen readers in Blackboard Collaborate. If you are using a mobile device or screen reader, you can share files and a blank whiteboard with your attendees.   Frequently Asked Questions   Should I schedule a Session or use the Course Room ? You can do either one. Just remember to inform your students/participants where to go.Â  Using Course Room is just like showing up to class. You simply Join the room and you are online. Just remember to show up on time! Scheduling a Session has some advantages. For example, you can have a session even without you.Â  Students can join and start presenting right away and the session can be automatically recorded.  How long does it take for a Blackboard Collaborate recording to publish? It can take up to a few hours for recordings to show up.   Alternatives   Webex : https://accc.uic.edu/services/communication-collaboration/conferencing/webex-meetings/  Zoom : https://accc.uic.edu/services/communication-collaboration/conferencing/zoom/  Google Hangouts : https://accc.uic.edu/services/communication-collaboration/conferencing/google-hangouts-meet/   UIC Blackboard Collaborate page: https://accc.uic.edu/services/communication-collaboration/conferencing/bb-collaborate/        Exams         Exams   During this unexpected time of remote learning, ACCC recommends that faculty use alternative assessment methods that avoid the need for secure, proctored exams. For tips on online testing and assessment alternatives, see this short Remote Assessments and Examinations tutorial .  If you must deliver an online exam and need a method to ensure academic integrity, UIC is offering faculty access (through May 31, 2020) to two online proctoring tools: Respondus LockDown Browser and Respondus Monitor.  Respondus is available only for exams conducted via Blackboard. Access it from the Tools menu in all Blackboard courses.  If you choose to use Respondus, please remember that students may be dealing with varied technology access and setups at home. We encourage you to be flexible to accommodate their remote arrangements.  Contact LTS@uic.edu with any questions about remote assessments or the Respondus tools.    Details on Respondus LockDown Browser and Respondus Monitor    Check ACCC webinar calendar for Respondus training               Meet Online   Resources for meetings, advising, office hours, and even teaching online. Learn more here >>      Webex         Webex Instructions   Get started   Sign In at https://uichicago.webex.com using Sign In button. Then enter your UIC netid and password.  Share the url just under your name (ends with your /netid) with your students over email.  Start a meeting by pressing the green Start a Meeting button (will install desktop app) or press arrow to select â€˜Use web appâ€™. Then press the Start a Meeting button.  Schedule a meeting with this video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O2aFzgXR4Sc   Instructions and Videos      Sign In instructions with pictures    Video: How to use Webex    Video: How to use Webex Personal Rooms    Video: How to Schedule a Meeting    Video: How to record Webex meetings    How to lock your room         Webex Notes   Notes   Start a meeting instantly without scheduling. Just share your Webex Personal Room url.  Lock your room or use Automatic Lock if you wish to keep it private until you admit people into the room.Â  People who join will wait in the Lobby until you admit them.        Webex FAQs   Frequently Asked Questions   If anyone can join my room, is it private or not? See â€˜What is a Room Lock?â€™ below.  What is a Room Lock? Learn more at https://help.webex.com/en-us/vjfafi/Lock-or-Unlock-Your-Cisco-Webex-Personal-Room  Why schedule a meeting? Scheduling a meeting gives you full control of who can come in and when. Create a topic/agenda, set password, set recurrence, allow another to host, and more.  Why schedule a meeting and not just start one? When you simply start a meeting itâ€™s like sitting in your office with the door open vs. closed. Door open scenario: Someone can show up and either walk in or wait outside until called. Room Lock feature explains it in detail. Door closed scenario: someone can show up and knock. You can let them in or ignore them. If you enable Automatic Lock , you will see them waiting in the Lobby and can choose if/when to let them into your room.        Webex Alternatives   Alternatives   Webex Teams is a virtual collaboration space for groups. Sign in with your UIC netid and password.   UIC Webex page: https://accc.uic.edu/services/communication-collaboration/conferencing/webex-meetings/ .        Zoom         Zoom Instructions   Get started   Sign In at https://uic.zoom.us/ . Then you can Host or Join a meeting.   Instructions and Videos    How do I get started with Zoom?    Video Tutorials    Video: How to record Zoom meetings    How to schedule Zoom meetings inside Blackboard    How do I protect my Zoom sessions (from "Zoombombing")?         Zoom Notes   Notes   When using the desktop app, always select â€˜ Sign in with SSO â€˜. Company domain should read â€˜ uic.zoom.us â€˜. Then you can log in with UIC netid and password.  Zoom use case disclaimer at https://techservices.illinois.edu/security/zoom-use-case-disclaimer .   UIC Zoom page: https://accc.uic.edu/services/communication-collaboration/conferencing/zoom/        Microsoft Teams         Teams Instructions   Get started   Sign In at http://teams.uic.edu/ using your UIC netid and password.   Instructions and Videos    Detailed instructions    Video: How to use Teams Demo    Video: Teams Training Modules         Teams Notes   UIC Microsoft Teams page: https://accc.uic.edu/services/communication-collaboration/virtual-collaboration-spaces/microsoft-teams/             Tips and Helpful Links     Best Practices         best practices    Good audio : Having good audio is crucial to minimize breaks in your voice. Use a microphone headset or any microphone/headphone combination you already have, including AirPods. Laptop audio often has their mic close to the speakers, creating a loop that will create breaks in sound for the listener of your lecture. Another way to fix when you lecture is to lower your speaker volume, be in a quiet room, and stay close to the laptop mic.  Dial In Numbers are a great way to bypass computer audio issues. However, with increased demand, some services are reporting issues. Check status links on https://bioe.uic.edu/teaching-online/ to view latest service disruption reports.  Turn off video camera : Only time you should use a camera is to say Hi! The rest of the time should be audio and screen share.  Mute everyone else when you are lecturing.Â  Peopleâ€™s mics will pick up background noises and create breaks in your lecture.  Share your screen : Donâ€™t forget to share your entire screen instead of individual applications. It is easier to swap between windows when you teach with multiple media.     Learn more about Netiquette & Best Practices          MATLAB         matlab    MATLAB for Students : Virtual application that runs on the Citrix server. Easy on studentsâ€™ computer resources.  MATLAB for Faculty : Powerful version that downloads and runs on faculty computer. Internet isrequired to connect to license server.  MATLAB for Faculty and Students (Free through June 30, 2020): All students, faculty and staff are eligible to download and install these products on their personally-owned computers or on university-issued computers. In addition, you will have browser access using MATLAB Online and MATLAB Drive. Learn more at https://webstore.illinois.edu/home/NewsItem.aspx?PostID=342         Webinars         webinars    Webinars and workshops available through ACCC         Online Safety         Online Safety   Few steps to help protect yourself from online threatsâ€¦  Accounts and passwords â€“ Regardless of how authentic emails may seem, when in doubt, you can always forward it to staff or security@uic.edu to confirm.Â  Examples include password change requests, account deactivation warnings. Anything odd then let us know ðŸ˜‰.  Email spoofing â€“ all too familiar for the past couple years, spoofing emails â€˜lookâ€™ like they are coming from people you know, but they are attacks in hopes that you reply. Unfortunately, there is nothing we can do to prevent such attacks. Information about our faculty is publicly available on websites and can easily be used to write a convincing email. Anyone can go to legitimate email services (gmail, yahoo, aolâ€¦) and create an address that looks almost like the real personâ€™s email. Such emails will keep coming, but here are a few tips to spot a spoof when the email just seems odd:   Donâ€™t reply!  Check for inconsistencies such as the email address, the signature, and context.  Always look at the actual email address, not the displayed name, to confirm who sent the email. This can be difficult with email clients on Smartwatch screens, phone notifications, or even computer email software (displays just the name, not the actual email address).  Be careful when drafting a fresh email to the real person. If you replied to the spoofed email, your email software might grab the spoofed address and save it to your address book. Be sure to delete it.   Additional recommended ACCC links for online safety:    ACCC Security Awareness site: Search for answers    Can you spot the phish?    I signed into a fake UIC website!    Passwords    Learn about Email Spoofing    How do I report a suspicious or threatening email?    Gift Card Email Scam Targeting UIC Faculty and Staff    Be vigilant of email scam attacks    Watch out for email, phone scams          Remote Access to Software         Remote Access to Specialized Software with Windows Virtual Desktop   Remote Access to Specialized Software with Windows Virtual Desktop:   Students â€“ you have been given access to this resource. Learn how to connect to Windows Virtual Desktop using a mobile device, desktop application and browser, and more: https://go.uic.edu/learn-more-windows-virtual-desktop  Instructors â€“ if you are interested in testing the Windows Virtual Desktop environment for any specialized software you expect students to use, please submit form at https://accc.uic.edu/forms/windows-virtual-des